Durban -  A 42-year-old man has been arrested for the killings that took place in a tavern along the south coast of KwaZulu-Natal. Captain Nqobile Gwala, police spokesperson, said the man was found in possession of an unlicensed firearm with 11 rounds of ammunition. Gwala said the firearm was seized and will undergo ballistic tests to determine whether it was used in any crimes. “The fourth victim who sustained gunshot wound to the head at Margate, later died in hospital,” she said. Major General Bheki Langa, KwaZulu-Natal Acting Provincial Commissioner said “We will not rest until the second suspect is apprehended. The detectives are working tirelessly to apprehend the remaining suspect. We are also appealing to anyone who may have information with regards to the suspects linked to the Umkomaas killing to contact their local police station or Crime Stop on 08600 10111.” Two armed men wearing balaclavas had entered a local tavern in Lamont near Margate. “At gunpoint they ordered all the patrons who were inside as well as outside the tavern to lie on the floor. The suspects opened fire at five people whilst the sixth victim was stabbed on the left leg. Three victims aged between 25 and 36 sustained gunshot wounds to the head and died on the scene. The other victims who sustained gunshot wounds to the head, arm and leg were taken to a local hospital for medical attention. The suspects stole money, liquor and a cellphone before fleeing the scene on foot,” Gwala said. She said the motive of the killing unknown but police are investigating charges of murder, attempted murder, assault with grievous bodily harm and robbery. Daily News